# Optical Character Recognition (OCR) System
### Advanced Digital Image Processing Framework

A high-performance OCR engine that converts non-editable pixel data (scanned documents, handwritten notes, industrial labels) into structured, searchable digital text using a custom Digital Image Processing (DIP) pipeline combined with the Tesseract LSTM engine.

##  Overview

Standard OCR engines often fail on real-world documents due to noise, uneven lighting, shadows, and broken character strokes. This project bridges that gap with a **custom pre-processing pipeline** that "cleans" raw images before they are passed to Tesseract — dramatically improving recognition accuracy.

> Bridging Physical Gaps: enabling the seamless transition from "static ink" to "active data" for automated workflows and large-scale analytics.

##  The DIP Pipeline

The Digital Image Processing pipeline is the core engine room of the system, transforming raw, noisy images into clean inputs before character recognition.

### Phase 1: Noise Removal — Advanced Denoising
- Removes digital "salt-and-pepper" noise and sensor graininess.
- Uses **Non-Local Means Denoising** to smooth background textures while preserving sharp text edges.

### Phase 2: Adaptive Thresholding — Illumination Correction
- Uses **Adaptive Gaussian Thresholding** to calculate local brightness per region (unlike global thresholding).
- Handles uneven lighting, paper shadows, and page curls, producing a pure black-on-white output.

### Phase 3: Structural Refinement — Morphological Closing
- Applies **Morphological Closing** (Dilation → Erosion) to heal small gaps in faint or broken characters.
- Produces solid, clean shapes that significantly boost the Tesseract LSTM engine's confidence score.

